'''Jane Bennett''' (born July 31, 1957)<ref name=Congress>{{cite web|title=Bennett, Jane, 1957-|url=http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n86032170.html|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=25 July 2014|quote=Her Unthinking faith and enlightenment, c1987: CIP t.p. (Jane Bennett) data sheet (b. 7/31/57)}}</ref> is an [[United States|American]] political theorist and philosopher. She is professor at the Department of Political Science, [[Johns Hopkins University School of Arts and Sciences#Departments|Johns Hopkins University School of Arts and Sciences]]. She is also the editor of the academic journal ''[[Political Theory (journal)|Political Theory]]''.<ref name=Pol_Theory>{{cite web|title=Political Theory: An International Journal of Political Philosophy|url=http://www.uk.sagepub.com/journalsProdDesc.nav?ct_p=manuscriptSubmission&prodId=Journal200749&crossRegion=eur|publisher=Sage|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref>

== Education ==
Jane Bennett originally trained in environmental studies and political science. She then went on to [[Cornell University]] to study environmental science. After Cornell she studied political theory and gained her degree (''[[Latin honors#Types|magna cum laude]]'') in 1979 from [[Siena College]], [[Loudonville, New York]]. Whilst at Siena College Bennett met [[Kathy Ferguson]]. Bennett then went on to the [[University of Massachusetts]] and qualified as a doctor of [[political science]] in 1986.<ref name=Minnesota_Review /><ref name=CV>{{cite web | title= Jane Bennett | url= http://politicalscience.jhu.edu/bios/jane-bennett/vita%202013%20November.doc | publisher= Department of Political Science, Johns Hopkins University | accessdate= 25 July 2014 }}</ref>

==Philosophical work==
Bennett's work considers [[ontology|ontological]] ideas about the [[Speculative realism#Transcendental Materialism / Neo-Vitalism|relationship between humans and 'things']], what she calls "vital materialism",
<blockquote>''"What counts as the material of vital materialism? Is it only human labour and the socio-economic entities made by men using raw materials? Or is materiality more potent than that? How can political theory do a better job of recognizing the active participation of nonhuman forces in every event and every stabilization? Is there a form of theory that can acknowledge a certain ‘thing-power’, that is, the irreducibility of objects to the human meanings or agendas they also embody?"''<ref name="Vital_materialism">{{Cite journal | last = Khan | first = Gulshan | title = Agency, nature and emergent properties: an interview with Jane Bennett | journal = Contemporary Political Theory | volume = 8 | issue = 1 | pages = 90–105 | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan | doi = 10.1057/cpt.2008.43 | date = February 2009 | url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1057/cpt.2008.43 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref></blockquote>

In her book, ''Vibrant Matter: A Political Ecology of Things'',<ref name=LAreview>[http://lareviewofbooks.org/essay/strawberries-on-life-support " Strawberries on Life Support by Antónia Szabari & Natania Meeker"]. ''Los Angeles Review of Books'']</ref> Bennett's argument is that, "Edibles, commodities, storms, and metals act as [[Agency (philosophy)|quasi agents]], with their own trajectories, potentialities and tendencies."<ref name=Minnesota_Review>{{Cite journal | last = Watson | first = Janell | title = Eco-sensibilities: interview with Jane Bennett | journal = Minnesota Review | volume = 81 | issue = 1 | pages = 147–158 | publisher = Duke University Press | doi = 10.1215/00265667-2332147 | date = October 2013 | url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1215/00265667-2332147 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref>

Public lectures she has given include "Impersonal Sympathy", a talk theorizing 'sympathy' in which she considered the alchemist-physician [[Paracelsus|Paracelsus (1493-1541)]] and [[Walt Whitman|Walt Whitman's]] collection of poetry, ''[[Leaves of Grass]]''.<ref name=CISSC>{{cite web|title=CISSC Lecture Series: Jane Bennett, Johns Hopkins University: Impersonal Sympathy |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728234301/http://cissc.concordia.ca/lecturesconferencesandevents/2012-13/?share=1|publisher=Center for Interdisciplinary Studies in Society and Culture, Concordia University, Montreal|accessdate=25 July 2014|date=22 March 2013}}</ref> In 2015 Bennett delivered the annual Neal A. Maxwell Lecture in Political Theory and Contemporary Politics at the University of Utah entitled “Walt Whitman and the Soft Voice of Sympathy.”

