{{refimprove|date=April 2014}} [[Image:pmel.gif|right]] The '''Pacific Marine Environmental Laboratory''' ('''PMEL''') is a laboratory in the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA) [[Office of Oceanic and Atmospheric Research]] (OAR). It is one of seven NOAA Research Laboratories (RLs).<ref>{{cite web |title = NOAA Research Laboratories |publisher = NOAA Office of Oceanic and Atmospheric Research |date = |url = http://ci.noaa.gov/NOAAResearchLaboratories.aspx |accessdate = 2014-04-26 |archiveurl = |archivedate = }}</ref> The PMEL is split across two sites in the Pacific Northwest, in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]] and [[Newport, Oregon|Newport]], [[Oregon]].
==Research== PMEL carries out interdisciplinary scientific investigations in [[oceanography]] and [[Earth's atmosphere|atmospheric]] science to improve our understanding of the complex physical and [[Geochemistry|geochemical]] processes operating in the world [[ocean]]s, especially the [[Pacific Ocean]], to define the forcing functions and the processes driving [[Ocean current|ocean circulation]] and the global [[climate]] system, and to improve environmental forecasting capabilities and other supporting services for marine commerce and [[Fishery|fisheries]].
